# Swift Project Organization

## Core Principle

Separate foundational/reusable code from application-specific code:

- **Foundational/Reusable Code** → `Core/` - Reusable across Swift projects
- **Application-Specific Code** → `App/` - Specific to this application

## Directory Structure

### Foundational Utilities (`Core/Utils/`)

Generic utilities reusable across projects:

- Platform-specific utilities (file system helpers, system integration)
- Framework configuration (logging, protocol handlers)
- System integration (window management, notifications, preferences)
- Generic helpers that work across different applications
- Reusable data models and types

These utilities have no dependencies on application-specific code and can be extracted for use in other projects.

### Application Utilities (`App/Utils/`)

Application-specific utilities:

- Feature-specific storage and data management
- Application-specific file operations
- Business logic specific to the application domain
- Domain-specific helpers and validators
- Application-specific data models

These utilities depend on application-specific types, data structures, or business logic.

### Foundational Views (`Core/Views/`)

Reusable SwiftUI views and UI components:

- Generic UI components (buttons, cards, inputs)
- Theme providers and utilities
- Reusable view modifiers
- Generic layout components
- Shared view extensions

These views are reusable and not tied to specific application features. They conform to SwiftUI's View protocol and follow SwiftUI conventions.

### Application Views (`App/`)

Application-specific views and features:

- Application entry point (App struct with @main attribute)
- Feature-specific views and screens
- Domain-specific components
- Application-specific layouts
- Business logic views

These views implement application-specific functionality and UI.

## Recommended Project Structure

For better organization, consider this structure:

```
YourApp/
├── YourApp/
│   ├── App/
│   │   ├── YourAppApp.swift      # App entry point
│   │   ├── AppDelegate.swift     # App lifecycle (if needed)
│   │   ├── Views/
│   │   │   ├── ContentView.swift     # Main view
│   │   │   └── Components/           # Application-specific UI components
│   │   ├── Models/
│   │   │   └── YourModel.swift       # Application-specific data models
│   │   ├── Services/
│   │   │   └── YourService.swift     # Application-specific business logic
│   │   └── Utils/
│   │       └── Extensions.swift      # Application-specific helper extensions
│   ├── Core/
│   │   ├── Utils/
│   │   │   └── CoreUtility.swift     # Reusable utilities
│   │   └── Views/
│   │       └── CoreComponent.swift  # Reusable UI components
│   └── Assets.xcassets/              # Resources
├── YourAppTests/
└── YourApp.xcodeproj/
```

This structure follows the Core/App separation principle:
- **App/** - All application-specific code (App entry, Views, Models, Services, Utils)
- **Core/** - Reusable/foundational code (utilities, views, and components that can be extracted)

## Rules

### ✅ DO

- Place reusable Swift utilities in `Core/Utils/`
- Place application-specific utilities in `App/Utils/`
- Place reusable SwiftUI views in `Core/Views/`
- Place application-specific views in `App/`
- Keep foundational code independent of application code
- Make foundational utilities importable by application code
- Use SwiftUI naming conventions (Views not Components)
- Keep resources like asset catalogs at the root level

### ❌ DON'T

- Mix foundational and application-specific code
- Place application-specific logic in foundational utilities
- Place reusable utilities in application directories
- Create dependencies from foundational code to application code
- Include application-specific types or data in foundational code
- Use non-SwiftUI terminology for UI components

## Benefits

- **Reusability**: Foundational code can be extracted for other projects
- **Clear boundaries**: Easy to identify what's reusable vs application-specific
- **Maintainability**: Clear separation makes code easier to understand and modify
- **Template-friendly**: Foundation code serves as a reusable template
- **Scalability**: Easy to add new features without affecting foundational code
- **SwiftUI conventions**: Follows standard Swift/SwiftUI naming and structure patterns
